title: For Sale:  270 Weatherby Magnum Custom Built Rife
postcontent:
The rifle is a bolt action rifle assembled using the very best parts by a custom gunsmith - a custom-build.  It has a “exquisite” walnut monte-carlo stock.  The barrel is chrome vanadium made by FN Browning in Belgium.  The receiver is a custom Mauser action.  The caliber is 270 Weatherby, which is a super charged 270 wm.  Bullets should be available at the local upper-level sportsman gun orientated outlets and at Cabalas.  The trigger and bullet loading housing is nicely and fully engraved.  The rifle is very finely blued and the stock elegantly finished walnut with simply outstanding grain.  Also, suspect many coats of finishing oil.

 It comes with a very clear Bausch & Lomb Balvar 50mm X 3-9 variable scope in black satin finish (might be 8mm objective lens).  Frankly, it is one of the “finest” grained walnut wood stocks I have ever seen.  Because it is in such a “new” condition and is such a “looker” I am certain it has never been out hunting.  I have had it about 8 years and felt it is simply too gorgeous to take out and subject it to the normal field hunting nicks and scratches.  I originally bought it for its great looks only.  One feels especially nice  simply looking at it.   

 Frankly, it is so nice it should be highly attractive for one whom has a very high appreciation for the best in custom built rifles using the finest of wood grained walnut stocks.  I would like to see it go to folks whom really appreciate superb grained wood and the classic elegant lines in fine rifles. 
It is ready for deer/elk hunting immediately.  Final purchase is conditional to full compliance with the Colorado State law.

This bag has been loaded and unloaded with supplies, but has NEVER BEEN USED outside the house or in the field. 

Pockets for everything, plenty of built in straps and hooks, the perfect tactical bag. I'm moving and don't have a need for this at my new place. This bag is NEW, all seams and zippers are in perfect condition. Not a thread is out of place. 

Save yourself the shipping costs and hassle of buying something online that you haven't seen. See for yourself that this bag is in pristine condition.

My model is Coyote Tan in color.

This exact bag goes for over $100.00 online in cost and shipping.

Manufacturer's Specs:
This MOLLE compatible pack splits the difference between our small assault pack and our larger Tobago bag, proving a good deal of carrying capacity in a straight-forward, comfortable design that maximizes the available volume.
At 19" x 15" x 8" with two main compartments and two large pockets, this pack is plenty big enough for most activities in the field. But if you need to haul more gear, you will find it is covered with MOLLE webbing attachment points, or PALs, so that you can add more pouches. It even has them on the bottom so you can attach bedding. The waist belt provides even more attachment points and is perfect for hanging a first aid kit, magazine or other pouches.

As you would expect, it has a built in compartment for your hydration bladder (not included) and your choice of three hose exit positions. It has a heavy duty rubber drag handle and the back is compression molded and contoured for the maximum comfort against your back. The wide straps are cushioned and offer additional attachment points. Other features include d-rings, removable padded kidney belt with quick release buckle, and fully adjustable contoured shoulder straps.

The controls are uniquely American, influenced by such famous designs as the Government Model 1911 pistol.

All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. HK pioneered this use of polymer materials in the production of handguns more than 30 years ago with the development of the VP70Z and P9S pistols.

The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.

Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance. It functions effectively in all USP models.

The modular design of the USP's internal components allows the control lever function to be switched from the left to the right side of the pistol for left-handed shooters.

The USP can also be converted from one type of trigger firing mode to another. This includes combination double-action and single-action (DA/SA) modes and double action only (DAO) modes.

HK USP 45 compact Features:

Corrosion proof fiber-reinforced polymer frame - Polygonal bore profile for increased velocity, easier cleaning, and longer barrel life - Can be converted to any of nine trigger firing modes - Corrosion resistant “Hostile Environment” blued finish - Oversized trigger guard for use with gloves - One piece machined slide made from nitro-carburized steel - Universal mounting grooves for installing accessories - Ambidextrous magazine release lever - Extended slide release - Patented Lock-Out Safety device

title: For Sale:  Very early Charter Arms .38 Undercover
location: Santa Fe, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
This revolver was made in 1967, when Charter Arms was a highly respected American handgun manufacturer. They were used by police all over the country, and even carried by American pilots  in Vietnam because they weighed only 16 ounces and were reliable handguns with aircraft aluminum frames and modular construction. Ruger basically copied much of the design when they came out with the much larger Security Six later in the decade. In many ways, they are superior to the design of the S&W AirLite or Chiefs Special. There is no sideplate to screw up and the solid frame is stronger because of that.

This specific revolver is in almost mint condition with no wear to the action, and no holster wear either. I wrote "almost" because there is a 1mm scratch near the hammer on the right side. It doesn't go all the way through the finish, but it is there. You can see it in my second photo, and it looks worse in the picture than it actually is. The casehardening colors on the hammer and trigger are strong, and the frame anodizing has turned a pleasant plum color with age. This anodizing process appears to be tougher than most modern aluminum treatments,  and is similar to the finish found on classic Leupold scopes. I know because I used to work for Leupold. 

This Undercover .38 has the relatively rare 3 inch barrel. It is about as concealable as a 2 inch, but it is MUCH easier to shoot accurately. It fits in a pocket just great, and while this one is unaltered, many people bobbed the hammers for just that reason. It particularly  likes any 158 grain .38 Special ammo, and the sights on it seem to be regulated for that. No Coke can has been safe within 35 yards, and frankly empty shotgun shells are an easy target at 25. The trigger and action are at least the equal of about any currently produced S&W,  and far superior to the current crop of Taurus and Ruger revolvers as well. The fit and finish are amazing, as are the internals. It makes me wonder why we accept the sometimes-junkers that are being produced these days for two or three times my asking price.

At any rate, this one is as tight, crisp, and smooth as the day it came off the line in Bridgeport, CT in 1967...By the way, it is light and accurate enough to not only conceal well, but also to make just a great trail gun or hunting back-up. Remember, with a revolver you never have to worry about a jam or finicky ammo. Pull the trigger and it goes bang. Every time. Not sexy these days I guess, but they just work.

You will NOT be disappointed when you see this gun, and will  be extremely happy when you shoot it. I am only selling it and another gun here to fund an antique that I have been trying to find for a long time. 

Contact me through Armslist with your phone number and I will call or text you to meet and see it. Once again, thanks for wading through all of this. Your reward for reading this far is a box with 40 American Eagle 158 grain .38 Specials when you buy the gun so you can enjoy it right away. Free. Of course, the little plastic case that I fitted it in is also included. The gun was too nice to not have SOME kind of case, lol.

All the best,
Doby Pilgrim
Santa Fe

title: For Sale:  Llama Micro Max .380 enhanced
location: Santa Fe, New Mexico, United States
postcontent:
This Llama is one of the very last in a long, long, line of them to be produced. As you can see it is basically a miniature version of the Colt 1911, and it does have a spare magazine with plastic bump pad. It has all the modern enhancement features that make it very shootable, such as the extended beavertail grip safety, enlarged slide release , wide manual safety, and extended magazine release. The feed ramp has been polished so it will shoot hollow points reliably, and it has a Commander hammer. Sights are modern 3 dot style and it shoots to point of aim. It is also quite accurate, giving me 2 to 3 inch groups at 25 yards. Finish is deep polished blue over Electroless nickel. The gun comes with the stag grips as shown, and the black original factory grips as well. The factory grips are in perfect condition, but I thought this gun deserved a set of custom grips, so I had the faux stags made for it. They are quite comfortable and well-fitted. 

I have owned this pistol for several years,  and even before I polished the feed ramp, I had never had a single jam, misfired, or failure to feed or eject. It has been dead reliable. Not all Llamas are like this of course. Llama seemed to take particular pride in these little 1911 clones, and this one is a really good one. It is after all hard to improve on perfection, and as I say, this Micromax has had a perfect reliability record with me. I used to collect these, and the fact that this is my last one says something. It was and is my favorite. 

These are safe to carry cocked and locked,  since they have all the safety features of the greatest fighting handgun in  history, the Colt 1911. They have been used by sportsmen and police all over the world since before WWII, and the Spanish even sold them to Germany for use by pilots, aircrew, and officers. With their size and features, it is easy to see why. I have pictured it with a pair of my sunglasses to show the size in case you haven't handled one. Even though they are small, they seem to fit many different sized hands, and I have found it to be one of the most comfortable-shooting semiautos I have ever shot. 

This gun is all steel, and no plastic was killed in the manufacture of it lol. You can buy cheaper .380s out there. There are plenty of nice and cheap plastic guns that work just fine. However, these little Llamas might actually turn out to be less expensive in the long run, since they actually appreciate in value unlike the plastic fantastic guns we get nowadays. Heck, even I have an LCP. I keep it in my car and if it got stolen I would be upset, but not exactly devastated if you know what I mean. When at the range, nobody ever came up to me and got excited to see my LCP. These Llamas are quite a bit more shootable, and much to my surprise, they have become quite collectible as well.

As with my other ad here, if you have had the patience to read all the way through this long winded advertisement, your reward is a fresh box of ammo for it included in the price. You also get the concealment book case I made up for it.

Contact me through Armslist with your phone number or email, and I will call you to arrange a time and place to meet.

All the best,
Doby Pilgrim
Santa Fe, NM

title: For Sale/Trade:  Traxxas E-Revo Brushless Edition and Traxxas E-Maxx Brushless Edition
postcontent:
My E-revo was adult owned and not bashed. I no longer have time for this hobby due to work and other commitments. 

First up for sale is my Traxxas E-Revo brushless edition. I bought this in July 2012. I've only driven it a handful of times, it's never seen water or been abused in any way. It's only been ran on 4s and 5s. (I've only ran it on 5s two or three times). It's basically stock except the red aluminum pushrods and the tires/wheels are from an Emaxx. This truck is very fast and will pull wheelies all day long!

It will come with all the original parts/accessories and also additional accessories and parts (all are pictured).
Also included (as pictured)
* Turnigy Nano-tech 2s 5000mah 45-90c lipo battery (only 2-3 cycles on battery)
* Turnigy Nano-tech 3s 5000mah 45-90c lipo battery (only 2-3 cycles on battery)
* Onyx 235 charger (has built-in balancer)
* Team Integy allen set

The truck is in great condition, normal scratches here and there. Everything mechanical and electrical work as they should. The E-revo body is in very good shape. The Emaxx body that it comes with is in decent condition, not a ton of life left in that one.

I'm asking $550 or similar value on a trade.


_______________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Next is the E-maxx brushless edition. I've only owned this for about a month. I bought it from an individual from Craigslist. He had bought it new about a year ago. It's a good truck. He had plasti-dipped (ie, waterproofed) the ESC. I didn't care for the fact that he did that (mainly b/c it voids the warranty). But anyway, I removed the plasti-dip from the ESC as soon as I got it home and the truck performs just as it should electronically. He had also stated he replaced the rear-diff a few months ago. He had also only ran it on 6s (the two mismatched lipo's as pictured)

With that said, I've only driven the truck on three occasions (all driven on 4s, with the 2s batteries pictured). I had to replace a few parts on the truck and it's running as it should now. The slipper clutch might need a little adjustment for though. 

I'm including the blue body he included (poor condition) and a new-ish red EMBE body. 
Also included:
* 2 - Turnigy Nano-tech 2s 5000mah 45-90c lipos (only about 5-7 cycles on these)
* 2 - 3s 4000mah 20-25c lipos (Onyx and Venom are the brands)
* Onyx 230 charger
* Equinox Lipo balancer

I'm asking $450 or similar value on a trade.
